                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d900">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense(M)Turkey/994: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-19T23:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 19, 1944—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 20—11:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>714. I have had a talk this morning with my British colleague on subject of
                    chrome. It was agreed between us I should have a further talk with Foreign
                    Minister in course of next few days with a view to endeavoring to persuade him
                    to agree to a further reduction from 4,000 tons monthly in shipments to Germany.
                    As Department and FEA doubtless appreciate, matter of obtaining further
                    reductions in the shipments of Turk chrome to Germany will be a part of our <pb
                        facs="0843" n="831" xml:id="pg_831"/> general discussions with the Turks
                    growing out of the Anglo-American Joint Declaration. My British colleague and I
                    are not without hope of ultimate success in effecting a further substantial
                    reduction in shipments of chrome to Germany. Much will depend on our ability in
                    the course of general discussions to guarantee Turk requirements of commodities
                    which the Turks have been and are receiving from the Axis countries.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
